A056004.name: Initial step in Goodstein sequences: write n in hereditary representation base 2, bump to base 3, then subtract 1.

A056007.name: Difference between 2^n and largest square strictly less than 2^n.

A056008.name: Difference between (smallest square strictly greater than 2^n) and 2^n.

A056009.name: a(n) = (n^n + 1)/ (n^(2^a) + 1), where 2^a is the highest power of 2 dividing n.

A056010.name: Number of words of length n in a simple grammar.

A056014.name: a(n) = (Fibonacci(2n-1) - Fibonacci(n+1))/2.
formula: Convolution of Fibonacci numbers F(n) with F(2n). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jun 07 2004
G.f.: x^3/((1 - x - x^2)*(1 - 3*x + x^2)). - _Herbert Kociemba_, Jun 16 2004

Convolution of the powers of 2 (A000079) with the number of positive rational knots with 2n+1 crossings (A051450), with three leading zeros. - _Graeme McRae_, Jun 28 2006

A056020.name: Numbers that are congruent to +-1 mod 9.

formula: T(n, k) = (n^2 - (n - 2*k)*(-1)^(n mod 2))/2 + n mod 2. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 25 2004

A056038.name: Largest factorial k! such that (k!)^2 divides n!.

A056039.name: Largest k such that (k!)^2 divides n!.

A056040.name: Swinging factorial, a(n) = 2^(n-(n mod 2))*Product_{k=1..n} k^((-1)^(k+1)).
formula: a(2*n) = binomial(2*n,n); a(2*n+1) = (2*n+1)*binomial(2*n,n). Central terms of triangle A211226. - _Peter Bala_, Apr 10 2012
D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) + (n-2)*a(n-1) + 4*(-2*n+3)*a(n-2) + 4*(-n+1)*a(n-3) + 16*(n-3)*a(n-4) = 0. - _Alexander R. Povolotsky_, Aug 17 2012
E.g.f.: U(0) where U(k)= 1 + x/(1 - x/(x + (k+1)*(k+1)/U(k+1))); (continued fraction, 3-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 19 2012
Central column of the coefficients of the swinging polynomials A162246. - _Peter Luschny_, Oct 22 2013
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} A189231(n, 2*k). (Cf. A212303 for the odd case.) - _Peter Luschny_, Oct 30 2013

A056041.name: Value for which b(a(n))=0 when b(2)=n and b(k+1) is calculated by writing b(k) in base k, reading this as being written in base k+1 and then subtracting 1.

a(n) = Sum_{k=1..A000005(n)} A007318(n, A027750(k)). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Aug 13 2013

A056046.name: Number of 3-antichain covers of a labeled n-set.

A056052.name: Number of 7-antichain covers of a labeled n-set.

formula: The next term is approximately the previous term * e^2.
a(n) = A092315(n)*2 + 1 = floor(exp(n*2-Euler)/4+1/8)*2+1 for all n (conjectured). - _M. F. Hasler_, Jan 24 2017

A056054.name: a(n) = smallest even number 2m such that value of odd harmonic series Sum_{j=0..m} 1/(2j) is > n.
formula: The next term is approximately the previous term * e^2.

formula: E.g.f.: A(2x) - A(x) where A(x) is the e.g.f. for A001187. - _Geoffrey Critzer_, Sep 09 2013

A056068.name: Numbers n such that n! is divisible by the square of (f+d)!^2 for d=0, 1 and 2 (and possibly larger d), where f=floor[n/2]

A056075.name: Numbers n such that n divides sigma(n) - d(n).
formula: Numbers n such that A000203(n) (mod n) == A000005(n) or A054024(n)=A000005(n). - _Labos Elemer_, Apr 12 2002

A056081.name: Numbers that are congruent to {1,26} mod 27.

A056113.name: Most significant digit of n-th primorial A002110.

A056115.name: a(n) = n*(n+11)/2.
formula: a(n) = A126890(n,5) for n>4. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Dec 30 2006

A056119.name: a(n) = n*(n+13)/2.
formula: a(n) = A126890(n,6) for n > 5. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Dec 30 2006
If we define f(n,i,a) = Sum_{k=0..n-i} binomial(n,k)*Stirling1(n-k,i)*Product_{j=0..k-1} (-a-j), then a(n) = -f(n,n-1,7), for n >= 1. - _Milan Janjic_, Dec 20 2008
a(n) = n + a(n-1) + 6 (with a(0)=0). - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 07 2010
a(n) = 7*n - floor(n/2) + floor(n/2). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 15 2013

A056121.name: a(n) = n*(n + 15)/2.

a(n) = a(n-1)+ n + 7 (with a(0)=0). - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 07 2010
a(n) = 8*n - floor(n/2) + floor(n^2/2). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 15 2013
E.g.f.: x*(16 + x)*exp(x)/2. - _G. C. Greubel_, Jan 18 2020

A056126.name: a(n) = n*(n + 17)/2.
formula: a(n) = A126890(n,8) for n>7. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Dec 30 2006
If we define f(n,i,a) = Sum_{k=0..n-i} binomial(n,k)*stirling1(n-k,i)* Product_{j=0..k-1} (-a-j), then a(n) = -f(n,n-1,9), for n>=1. - _Milan Janjic_, Dec 20 2008
a(n) = a(n-1) + n + 8 (with a(0)=0). - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 07 2010
a(n) = 9*n - floor(n/2) + floor(n^2/2). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 15 2013
E.g.f.: x*(18 + x)*exp(x)/2. - _G. C. Greubel_, Jan 19 2020

A056132.name: Sequence A001033 gives the numbers n such that the sum of the squares of n consecutive odd numbers x^2 + (x+2)^2 + ... +(x+2n-2)^2 = k^2 for some integer k. For each n, this sequence gives the least value of k.

formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=0} x^k/(1 - k!*x). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Oct 09 2018

A056194.name: Characteristic cube divisor of n!: a(n) = A056191(n!).

A056195.name: a(n) = n! divided by its characteristic cube divisor A056194.

A056199.name: a(n) = n * a(n-1) - Sum_{k=1..n-2} a(k) with a(1) = 0 and a(2) = 1.

a(n) = A007489(n)/3 for n >= 2. - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 10 2007
G.f.: x*(W(0)/(2-2*x)/3 -1/3), where W(k) = 1 + 1/( 1 - x*(k+2)/( x*(k+2) + 1/W(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 20 2013

formula: Binomial transform of A087205. Binomial transform is A087206. - _Paul Barry_, Aug 25 2003
2nd inverse binomial transform of Fibonacci(3n+2). - _Paul Barry_, Apr 16 2004
a(n+1) = (k^floor((n+1)/2) + k^ceiling((n+1)/2)) / 2, where k=5 is the number of possible colors. - _Robert A. Russell_, Sep 22 2018

a(n) = (k^floor((n+1)/2) + k^ceiling((n+1)/2)) / 2, where k = 6 is the number of possible colors. - _Robert A. Russell_, Sep 22 2018

A056489.name: Number of periodic palindromes using exactly three different symbols.
formula: a(n) = (k!/2)*(S2(floor((n+1)/2),k) + S2(ceiling((n+1)/2),k)), with k=3 different colors used and where S2(n,k) is the Stirling subset number A008277. - _Robert A. Russell_, Jun 05 2018

A056490.name: Number of periodic palindromes using exactly four different symbols.

A056491.name: Number of periodic palindromes using exactly five different symbols.

A056492.name: Number of periodic palindromes using exactly six different symbols.

A056493.name: Number of primitive (period n) periodic palindromes using a maximum of two different symbols.
formula: Sum_{d|n} mu(d)*b(n/d), where b(n) = A029744(n+1). [Corrected by _Petros Hadjicostas_, Oct 15 2017. The original formula referred to a previous version of sequence A029744 that had a different offset.]

More generally, let gf(k) be the g.f. for the number of necklaces with reflectional symmetry but no rotational symmetry and beads of k colors. Then gf(k): Sum_{n >= 1} mu(n)*Sum_{i=0..2} binomial(k,i)*x^(n*i)/(1 - k*x^(2*n)). - _Herbert Kociemba_, Nov 29 2016

G.f.: Sum_{n >= 1} mu(n)*x^n*(2 + 3*x^n)/(1 - 2*x^(2*n)). The g.f. by _Herbet Kociemba_ above, with k = 2, becomes Sum_{n>=1} mu(n)*(x^n + 1)^2/(1 - 2*x^(2*n)). The two formulae differ by the "undetermined" constant Sum_{n >= 1} mu(n). - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Oct 15 2017

A056525.name: Palindromes with odd number of digits.

formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-4) - a(n-5) for n>5. - _Harvey P. Dale_, Apr 05 2015

A056528.name: Sum of digits of square of sum of digits of square.

A056529.name: Number of iterations of sum of digits of square to reach 1, 9, 13 or 16.

A056531.name: Sequence remaining after a fourth round of Flavius Josephus sieve; remove every fifth term of A056530.

A056533.name: Even sieve: start with natural numbers, remove every 2nd term, remove every 4th term from what remains, remove every 6th term from what remains, etc.

A056534.name: Mapping from the ordering by product (A027750, A056538) to the ordering by sum (A002260, A004736) of ordered pairs (a,b), a>=1, b>=1.

A056535.name: Mapping from the ordering by sum to the ordering by product of the ordered pairs. Inverse permutation to A056534.

A056536.name: Mapping from half-antidiagonal reading of the triangle (as used in A028297) to the column-by-column reading of the triangular tables.

A056537.name: Mapping from the column-by-column reading to the half-antidiagonal reading of the triangular tables. Inverse of A056536.
formula: Triangle T(n, k), 1<=k<=n, read by rows, defined by: T(n, k) = 0 for n<k and T(n, k) = A002620(n-k+1) + k*n + k - n if n>=k. T(n, n) = n^2; T(n, 1) = 1 + A002620(n) = A033638(n). - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 16 2004

A056538.name: Irregular triangle read by rows: row n lists the divisors of n in decreasing order.

A056539.name: Self-inverse permutation: reverse the bits in binary expansion of n and also complement them (0->1, 1->0) if the run count (A005811) is even.

A056540.name: a(1) = 1; to form a(n+1), append a(n)-1, a(n)+1 at the beginning and the end of a(n), respectively. Ignore any leading 0's.

A056541.name: a(n) = 2n*a(n-1) + 1 with a(0)=0.
formula: a(n) = Sum[P(n, k) * 2^k {k=0 to n-1}] - _Ross La Haye_, Sep 15 2004
a(n) = 2^n*n!*Sum_{k=1..n}{1/(k!*2^k)}, with n>=0. - _Paolo P. Lava_, Apr 26 2010

A056543.name: a(n) = n*a(n-1) - 1 with a(1)=1.
formula: a(n) = n!*(2-Sum_{k=1..n}{k!^(-1)}), with n>=1. - _Paolo P. Lava_, Jun 25 2010

A056544.name: Smallest palindrome containing the digits of n as a subsequence.

A056545.name: a(n) = 4*n*a(n-1) + 1 with a(0)=1.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} P(n, k)*4^k. - _Ross La Haye_, Aug 29 2005
a(n) = exp(1/4)*4^n*Gamma(n+1, 1/4). a(n) ~ sqrt(2*Pi)*4^n*n^(n+1/2)*exp(1/4-n). - _Vladimir Reshetnikov_, Oct 14 2016
The e.g.f. y = exp(x)/(1 - 4*x) satisfies the differential equation (1 - 4*x)*y' = (5 - 4*x)*y.

The sequence b(n) := 4^n*n! also satisfies the same recurrence with b(0) = 1, b(1) = 4. This leads to the continued fraction representation a(n) = 4^n*n!*( 1 + 1/(4 - 4/(9 - 8/(13 - ... - (4*n - 4)/(4*n + 1) )))) for n >= 2. Taking the limit gives the continued fraction representation exp(1/4) = 1 + 1/(4 - 4/(9 - 8/(13 - ... - (4*n - 4)/((4*n + 1) - ... )))). Cf. A010844. (End)

A056546.name: a(n) = 5*n*a(n-1) + 1 with a(0)=1.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} P(n, k)*5^k. - _Ross La Haye_, Aug 29 2005
The e.g.f. y = exp(x)/(1 - 5*x) satisfies the differential equation (1 - 5*x)*y' = (6 - 5*x)*y.

The sequence b(n) := 5^n*n! also satisfies the same recurrence with b(0) = 1, b(1) = 5. This leads to the continued fraction representation a(n) = 5^n*n!*( 1 + 1/(5 - 5/(11 - 10/(16 - ... - (5*n - 5)/(5*n + 1) )))) for n >= 2. Taking the limit gives the continued fraction representation exp(1/5) = 1 + 1/(5 - 5/(11 - 10/(16 - ... - (5*n - 5)/((5*n + 1) - ... )))). Cf. A010844. (End)

A056547.name: a(n) = 6*n*a(n-1) + 1 with a(0)=1.
formula: a(n) = n!*Sum_{k=0..n} 6^(n-k)/k!. E.g.f.: exp(x)/(1 - 6*x). - _Philippe Deléham_, Mar 14 2004
The e.g.f. y = exp(x)/(1 - 6*x) satisfies the differential equation (1 - 6*x)*y' = (7 - 6*x)*y.

The sequence b(n) := 6^n*n! also satisfies the same recurrence with b(0) = 1, b(1) = 6. This leads to the continued fraction representation a(n) = 6^n*n!*( 1 + 1/(6 - 6/(13 - 12/(19 - ... - (6*n - 6)/(6*n + 1) )))) for n >= 2. Taking the limit gives the continued fraction representation exp(1/6) = 1 + 1/(6 - 6/(13 - 12/(19 - ... - (6*n - 6)/((6*n + 1) - ... )))). Cf. A010844. (End)

A056548.name: a(n) = Sum_{k>=1} round(n/k) where round(1/2) = 0.
formula: Conjecture: a(n) = Sum_{k=n..2n-1} d(k), where d is the number of divisors function (A000005). - _Ridouane Oudra_, Apr 29 2019

A056549.name: a(n) = Sum_{k>=1} round(n/k) where round(1/2)=1.
formula: Conjecture: a(n) = n + Sum_{k=1..n} floor(n/k + 1/2) = n + A077024(n). - _Ridouane Oudra_, Apr 29 2019

A056550.name: Numbers n such that sum_{k=1..n} sigma(k) is divisible by n, where sigma(k) = sum of divisors of k (A000203).
formula: Values of n for which A024916(n)/n is integer.
Also values of n for which A004125(n)/n is integer. [_Paolo P. Lava_, Jan 08 2013]

A056551.name: Smallest cube divisible by n divided by largest cube which divides n.

A056552.name: Powerfree kernel of cubefree part of n.

A056553.name: Smallest 4th-power divisible by n divided by largest 4th-power which divides n.

A056554.name: Powerfree kernel of 4th-powerfree part of n.
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = p^(if 4|e, then 0, else 1).

A056555.name: Smallest number k (k>0) such that n*k is a perfect 4th power.
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = p^((4 - e) mod 4). - _Amiram Eldar_, Sep 08 2020

A056556.name: First tetrahedral coordinate; repeat m (m+1)*(m+2)/2 times.
formula: a(n) = floor(x) where x is the (largest real) solution to x^3 + 3x^2 + 2x - 6n = 0; a(A000292(n)) = n+1.
a(n+1) = a(n)+1 if a(n) = A056558(n), otherwise a(n). - _Graeme McRae_, Jan 09 2007
a(n) = floor(t/3 + 1/t - 1), where t = (81*n + 3*sqrt(729*n^2 - 3))^(1/3). - _Ridouane Oudra_, Mar 21 2021

A056557.name: Second tetrahedral coordinate.
formula: a(n+1) = 0 if A056556(n) = A056558(n); a(n+1) = a(n)+1 if a(n) = A056558(n); otherwise a(n+1) = a(n).  - _Graeme McRae_, Jan 09 2007

A056558.name: Third tetrahedral coordinate, i.e., tetrahedron with T(t,n,k)=k; succession of growing finite triangles with increasing values towards bottom right.

A056559.name: Tetrahedron with T(t,n,k) = t - n; succession of growing finite triangles with declining values per row.

A056560.name: Tetrahedron with T(t,n,k)=n-k; succession of growing finite triangles with increasing values towards bottom left.

A056561.name: Numbers n such that n^2 + n + 41 is prime.

A056562.name: Number of primes which are the difference between two triangular numbers, where the smaller is the n-th triangular number.
formula: a(n)=2 if both n+1 is prime and 2n+3 is prime, =1 if one of n+1 and 2n+3 is prime, =0 if neither are primes.

A056563.name: Number of primes which are the difference between two triangular numbers, where the larger is the n-th triangular number.
formula: a(n)=2 if both n is prime and 2n-1 is prime, =1 if one of n and 2n-1 is prime, =0 if neither are primes.

A056564.name: Number of times primes can be produced by taking the absolute difference between the n-th triangular number and another triangular number.
formula: a(n) =A056562(n)+A056563(n) =number of primes (with multiplicity) in {m, m+1, 2m-1, 2m+3}

A056565.name: Fibonomial coefficients.
formula: G.f.: 1/p(8, n) with p(8, n) = 1 - 21*x - 273*x^2 + 1092*x^3 + 1820*x^4 - 1092*x^5 - 273*x^6 + 21*x^7 + x^8 = (1 + x - x^2) * (1 - 4*x - x^2) * (1 + 11*x - x^2) * (1 - 29*x - x^2) (n=8 row polynomial of signed Fibonomial triangle A055870; see this entry for Knuth and Riordan references).

A056566.name: Fibonomial coefficients.
formula: G.f.: 1/p(9, n) with p(9, n)= 1 - 34*x - 714*x^2 + 4641*x^3 + 12376*x^4 - 12376*x^5 - 4641*x^6 + 714*x^7 + 34*x^8 - x^9 = (1-x)*(1 + 3*x + x^2)*(1 - 7*x + x^2)* (1 + 18*x + x^2)*(1 - 47*x + x^2) (n=9 row polynomial of signed Fibonomial triangle A055870; see this entry for Knuth and Riordan references).

A056567.name: Fibonomial coefficients.
formula: G.f.: 1/p(10, n) with p(10, n)= 1 - 55*x - 1870*x^2 + 19635*x^3 + 85085*x^4 - 136136*x^5 - 85085*x^6 + 19635*x^7 + 1870*x^8 - 55*x^9 - x^10 = (1 - x - x^2)*(1 + 4*x - x^2)*(1 - 11*x - x^2)*(1 + 29*x - x^2)*(1 - 76*x - x^2) (n=10 row polynomial of signed Fibonomial triangle A055870; see this entry for Knuth and Riordan references).

A056569.name: Row sums of Fibonomial triangle A010048.
formula: a(n)= sum(A010048(n, m), m=0..n); A010048(n, m)=: fibonomial(n, m).
c = EllipticTheta[3,0,1/GoldenRatio] / QPochhammer[-1/GoldenRatio^2] = 2.082828701647012450835512317685120373906427048806222527375... if n is even,
c = EllipticTheta[2,0,1/GoldenRatio] / QPochhammer[-1/GoldenRatio^2] = 2.082828691334156222136965926255238646603356514964103252122... if n is odd.

A056570.name: Third power of Fibonacci numbers (A000045).
formula: G.f.: x*p(3, x)/q(3, x) with p(3, x) = Sum_{m=0..2} A056588(2, m)*x^m = 1 -2*x -x^2 and q(3, x) = Sum_{m=0..4} A055870(4, m)*x^m = 1 -3*x -6*x^2 +3*x^3 +x^4 = (1+x-x^2)*(1-4*x-x^2) (factorization deduced from Riordan result).

Recursion (cf. Knuth's exercise): 1*a(n) -3*a(n-1) -6*a(n-2) +3*a(n-3) +1*a(n-4) = 0, n >= 4, a(0)=0, a(1)=a(2)=1, a(3)=2^3. See 5th row of signed Fibonomial triangle for coefficients: A055870(4, m), m=0..4

a(n) and a(n+1) are found as rightmost and leftmost terms (respectively) in M^n * [1 0 0 0] where M = the 4 X 4 upper triangular Pascal's triangle matrix [1 3 3 1 / 1 2 1 0 / 1 1 0 0 / 1 0 0 0]. E.g., Ma(4) = 27, a(5) = 125. M^4 * [1 0 0 0] = [125 75 45 27]; where 75 = A066259(4) and 45 = A066258(3). The characteristic polynomial of M = x^4 - 3x^3 - 6x^2 + 3x + 1. a(n)/a(n-1) of the sequence and companions tend to 2+sqrt(5) = 4.2360679..., an eigenvalue of M and a root of the polynomial. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Oct 31 2004
a(n) = F(n-1)*F(n)*F(n+1) + F(n)*(-1)^(n-1). - _Tony Foster III_, Apr 11 2018

A056571.name: Fourth power of Fibonacci numbers A000045.
formula: G.f.: x*p(4, x)/q(4, x) with p(4, x) := sum(A056588(3, m)*x^m, m=0..3) = 1 - 4*x - 4*x^2 + x^3 = (1+x)*(1 - 5*x + x^2) and q(4, x) := sum_{m=0..5} A055870(5, m)*x^m = 1 - 5*x - 15*x^2 + 15*x^3 + 5*x^4 - x^5 = (1-x)*(1 + 3*x + x^2)*(1 - 7*x + x^2) (denominator factorization deduced from Riordan result).
Recursion (cf. Knuth's exercise): 1*a(n) - 5*a(n-1) - 15*a(n-2) + 15*a(n-3) + 5*a(n-4) - 1*a(n-5) = 0, n >= 5; inputs: a(n), n=0..4.

A056572.name: Fifth power of Fibonacci numbers A000045.
formula: a(n) = (10*F(n) + 5*(-1)^(n+1)*F(3*n) + F(5*n))/25, n >= 0. See the general comment on A111418 regarding the Ozeki reference; here the row 10, 5, 1 of that triangle applies. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Aug 25 2012
a(n) = F(n-2)*F(n-1)*F(n)*F(n+1)*F(n+2) + F(n). - _Tony Foster III_, Apr 11 2018

A056573.name: Sixth power of Fibonacci numbers A000045.
formula: G.f.: x*p(6, x)/q(6, x) with p(6, x) := sum_{m=0..5} A056588(5, m)*x^m = (1-x)*(1 - 11*x - 64*x^2 - 11*x^3 + x^4) and q(6, x) := sum_{m=0..7} A055870(7, m)*x^m = (1+x)*(1 - 3*x + x^2)*(1 + 7*x + x^2)*(1 - 18*x + x^2) (denominator factorization deduced from Riordan result).

a(n+1) = 2*[2*F(n+1)^2-(-1)^n]^3+3*F(n)^2*F(n+1)^2*F(n+2)^2-[F(n)^6+F(n+2)^6] = {Sum(0 <= j <= [n/2]; binomial(n-j, j))}^6, for n (this is Theorem 2.2 (vi) of Azarian's second paper in the references for this sequence). - _Mohammad K. Azarian_, Jun 29 2015

A056574.name: Seventh power of Fibonacci numbers A000045.
formula: a(n+1) = F(n)^7+F(n+1)^7+7*F(n)*F(n+1)*F(n+2)*[2*F(n+1)^2-(-1)^n]^2 = {Sum(0 <= j <= [n/2]; binomial(n-j, j))}^7, for n>=0 (This is Theorem 2.3 (iv) of Azarian's second paper in the references for this sequence). - _Mohammad K. Azarian_, Jun 29 2015

A056575.name: Series for first parallel moment of square lattice bond percolation near a wall.

A056577.name: Difference between 3^n and highest power of 2 less than or equal to 3^n.

A056582.name: Highest common factor (or GCD) of n^n and hyperfactorial(n-1), i.e., gcd(n^n, product(k^k) for k < n).

A056583.name: Solution to a(n)^(n^2/a(n)) = gcd(n^n, Product_{k<n} k^k) where a(n) and n^2/a(n) are integers, or 0 if no such integers exist.
formula: a(2) = 1, a(4) = 0, a(8) = 16, a(9) = 27; if p an odd prime: a(p) = 1 and a(2p) = 4p; otherwise if n>1: a(n) = n. Apart from n = 4, a(n) = n^2/A056584(n) = A056582(n)^(1/A056584(n)).

A056584.name: Solution to (n^2/a(n))^a(n) = gcd(n^n, Product_{k<n} k^k) where a(n) and n^2/a(n) are integers, or 0 if no such integers exist.
formula: a(2) = 4, a(4) = 0, a(8) = 4, a(9) = 3; if p an odd prime: a(p) = p^2 and a(2p) = p; otherwise if n>1: a(n) = n. Apart from n = 4, a(n) = n^2/A056583(n) = log(A056582(n))/log(A056583(n)).

A056585.name: Eighth power of Fibonacci numbers A000045.
formula: a(n+1) = 8*F(n)^2*F(n+1)^2*[F(n)^4+F(n+1)^4+4*F(n)^2*F(n+1)^2+3*F(n)*F(n+1)*F(n+2)]-[F(n)^8+F(n+2)^8]+2*[2*F(n+1)^2-(-1)^n]^4 = {Sum(0 <= j <= [n/2]; binomial(n-j, j))}^8, for n>=0 (This is Theorem 2.2 (vii) of Azarian's second paper in the references for this sequence). - _Mohammad K. Azarian_, Jun 29 2015

A056586.name: Ninth power of Fibonacci numbers A000045.

A056587.name: Tenth power of Fibonacci numbers A000045.

A056588.name: Coefficient triangle of certain polynomials.
formula: a(n, m)=0 if n<m; a(n, 0)=1; a(n, m) = F(m+1)^(n+1) + sum(sfibonomial(n+2, j)*(F(m+1-j)^(n+1)), j=1..m) m=1..n, with F(n)=A000045(n) (Fibonacci) and sfibonomial(n, m) := A055870(n, m).
T(n, k) = Sum_{j=0..k} Fibonacci(k+1-j)^(n+1) * A055870(n+2, j). - _Tony Foster III_, Aug 20 2018
Sum_{j=0..n-1} a(n-1, n-1-j)*A010048(k+j, n) = Fibonacci(k)^n. - _Tony Foster III_, Jul 24 2018

A056589.name: Third column sequence of unsigned triangle A056588.

A056590.name: Fourth column sequence of triangle A056588.

A056591.name: Fifth column sequence of triangle A056588.

A056592.name: Row sums of signed triangle A056588.

A056593.name: Row sums of unsigned triangle A056588.

A056594.name: Periodic sequence 1,0,-1,0,...; expansion of 1/(1 + x^2).
formula: a(n) = (1/2)*((-i)^n + i^n), where i = sqrt(-1). - _Mitch Harris_, Apr 19 2005

Also a(n) = -a(n-2) for n>1; a(n) = A010892(A001651(n+1)); a(n) = (-(n mod 4)-(n+1 mod 4)+(n+2 mod 4)+(n+3 mod 4))/4 (cf. forms of modular arithmetic of _Paolo P. Lava_, see A146094). - _Bruno Berselli_, Feb 08 2011
a(n) = cos(n*Pi/2), with n>=0. - _Paolo P. Lava_, Aug 02 2006
a(n) = T(n, 0) = A053120(n, 0); T(n, x) Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Aug 21 2009
a(n) = S(n, 0)= A049310(n, 0); S(n, x) := U(n, x/2), Chebyshev polynomials of 2nd kind.
Sum_{k>=0} a(k)/(k+1) = Pi/4. - _Jaume Oliver Lafont_, Mar 30 2010

a(0) = 1, a(n-1) = 0 if n is even, a(n-1) = product((-1)^(e_j*(p_j-1)/2), j = 1..m) if the odd n-1 = p_1^(e_1)*p_2^(e_2)* ...*p_m^(e_m) with distinct odd primes p_j, j=1..m.  See the function h(n) of Theorem 5.12 of the Niven-Zuckerman reference. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Apr 19 2013
a(n) = (-4/(n+1)), n >= 0, where (k/n) is the Kronecker symbol. See the Eric Weisstein and Wikipedia links. Thanks to Wesley Ivan Hurt. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, May 31 2013

a(n) = R(n,0)/2 with the row polynomials R of A127672. This follows from the product of the zeros of R, and the formula Product_{k=0..n-1)} 2*cos((2*k+1)*Pi/(2*n)) = (1 + (-1)^n)*(-1)^(n/2), n >= 1 (see the Gradstein and Ryshik reference, p. 63, 1.396 4., with x = sqrt(-1)). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Oct 21 2013
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} i^(k*(k+1)), where i=sqrt(-1). - _Bruno Berselli_, Mar 11 2015
Dirichlet g.f. of a(n) shifted right: L(chi_2(4),s) = beta(s) = (1-2^(-s))*(d.g.f. of A034947), see comments by Lang and Forgues. - _Ralf Stephan_, Mar 27 2015

A056595.name: Number of nonsquare divisors of n.

A056596.name: Number of nonsquare divisors of n!.

A056597.name: Number of letters in n (in Serbian or Croatian).

A056598.name: Series for 2nd parallel moment of square lattice bond percolation near a wall (eventually goes negative).

A056599.name: Series for first perpendicular moment of square lattice bond percolation near a wall (eventually goes negative).

A056600.name: a(n) is smallest number A such that there is an equality of the form (A=Product of n distinct primes) = (B=Product of n distinct primes) + (C=Product of n distinct primes) with gcd(A,B) = gcd(B,C) = gcd(A,C) = 1, B < C.

A056601.name: Series for 2nd perpendicular moment of square lattice bond percolation near a wall (eventually goes negative).

A056602.name: Numbers A such that there is an equation of the form (A = Product of m + 1 primes) = (B = Product of m primes) + (C = Product of m primes), where A*B*C is a primorial number (A002110).

A056603.name: Squarefree kernels of distinct values of lcm(1,...,m) (A051451).

A056604.name: a(0)=1; thereafter a(n) = lcm(1, 2, 3, 4, ..., prime(n)).
formula: a(n) = prime(n)^r(n) *...* prime(1)^r(1) for maximal prime(j)^r(j) <= prime(n).

A056605.name: Number of stable n-celled patterns ("still lifes") in Conway's game of Life (incorrect version).

A056606.name: Squarefree kernel of lcm(binomial(n,0), ..., binomial(n,n)).
formula: a(n) = radical(hyperfactorial(n)/superfactorial(n)) = A007947(A002109(n)/ A000178(n)) for n >= 0. - _Peter Luschny_, Dec 21 2019

A056607.name: a(n) is the n-th primorial divided by squarefree kernel of corresponding central binomial coefficient.

A056608.name: Least prime factor of the n-th composite number.

A056609.name: a(n) = rad(n!)/rad(A001142(n)) where rad(n) is the squarefree kernel of n, A007947(n).

A056610.name: Quotient: squarefree kernel of lcm(1,..,n) (or of n!) divided by kernel of central binomial coefficient.

A056611.name: Quotient: squarefree kernel of A002944(n) divided by that of A001405.

A056613.name: Number of n-celled pseudo still lifes in Conway's Game of Life, up to rotation and reflection.

A056614.name: Number of n-celled P2-oscillators in Conway's game of Life.

A056616.name: Numerator of binomial(2n,n)/(2n+1).
formula: Numerators of the rationals r(n) = binomial(2n,n)/(2n+1) with G.f.: 1/(2*sqrt(x))*arcsin(2*sqrt(x)). [_Vladimir Kruchinin_, May 31 2013]

A056618.name: Concatenate factorials.
formula: a(n+1) = a(n)*10^floor(1 + log_10(n!)) + n!, with a(0)=1. - _Paolo P. Lava_, Jul 04 2008

A056619.name: Smallest prime with primitive root of n or 0 if no such prime exists.
formula: a(n) = 0 only for perfect squares, A000290.
a(n) = 2 for all odd n. a(n) = 0 for even squares. a(n) = 3 for n = 2 (mod 6). a(n) = 5 for n in {12, 18, 22, 28} (mod 30). - _M. F. Hasler_, Feb 21 2017

A056620.name: Free energy coefficients for square lattice spin 3 Ising model.

A056621.name: Series expansion for radius of gyration on square lattice.

A056622.name: Square root of largest unitary square divisor of n.
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = p^(e/2) if e even, a(p) = 1, and a(p^e) = p^((e-3)/2) for odd e > 1. - _Amiram Eldar_, Sep 14 2020

A056623.name: Largest unitary square divisor of n: if n=LLgggf (see A056192) and a(n) = LL, then its complementary divisor n/LL = gggf and gcd(L^2, n/LL) = 1.
formula: a(n) = A008833(n)/A055229(n)^2 = K^2/g^2, which coincides with the largest square divisor iff the g-factor is 1.
Multiplicative with a(p^e)=p^e for even e, a(p)=1, a(p^e)=p^(e-3) for odd e > 1. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 30 2002

A056624.name: Number of unitary square divisors of n.
formula: a(n) = 2^r, where r is the number of prime factors of the largest unitary square divisor of n.
Multiplicative with a(p^e) = 2^(1-(e mod 2)). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Dec 13 2002
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ n*Pi^2/(6*Zeta(3)) + sqrt(n)*Zeta(1/2)/Zeta(3/2). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 07 2019

A056625.name: Series expansion for first area weighted moment for square lattice.

A056626.name: Number of non-unitary square divisors of n.
formula: a(n) = A046951(n) - 2^r, where r is the number of prime factors in the largest unitary prime divisor of n.

A056627.name: Square root of largest unitary square divisor of n!.

A056628.name: Largest unitary square divisor of n!.

A056629.name: Number of unitary square divisors of n!.
formula: a(n) = 2^r, where r is the number of prime divisors of unitary analog of largest square divisor of n!, where r(n) = A001221[A000188(n!) /A055229(n!)].

A056630.name: Number of non-unitary square divisors of n!.
formula: a(n) = A046951(n!) - 2^r, where r is the number of prime divisors of unitary analog of largest square divisor of n! and  r(n) = A001221[A000188(n!)/A055229(n!)].

A056632.name: Series expansion for first perimeter weighted moment for square lattice.

A056636.name: Conjecturally largest even integer which is the sum of two primes in at most n ways.

formula: a(n+1) >= 2*a(n)+1, since a(n+1)-1 is even and must have a factor of class n- which is odd (n>1) and >= a(n). a(n+1) <= min { p = 2*k*a(n)+1 | k=1,2,3... such that p is prime }, since a(n) is a prime of class n-. - _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 05 2007

A056639.name: Number of polygons of length 2n with 3 (self-avoiding polygon) holes on square lattice (not allowing rotations).

formula: All numbers of the forms 5^k, 2*5^k & 6*5^k are in the sequence. - _Farideh Firoozbakht_, Nov 21 2006

A056646.name: Square root of largest unitary square divisor of central binomial coefficient.

A056647.name: Largest unitary square divisor of central binomial coefficient.

formula: a(n) = 2^r, where r is the number of prime factors in the largest unitary square(or square root) divisor of central binomial coefficient: r = A001221(A000188(A001405(n))/A055229(A001405(n))).

A056649.name: Number of non-unitary square divisors of central binomial coefficient.
formula: a(n) = A056061(n) - 2^r, where r is the number of prime factors in the largest unitary square (or square root) divisor of central binomial coefficient: r=A001221(A000188(A001405(n))/A055229(A001405(n))).

A056747.name: Raw solutions to Hi-Q puzzle with n holes on a side, any initial peg removed, final peg in top hole.

A056748.name: Raw solutions to Hi-Q puzzle with n holes on a side, any initial peg removed, final peg in initial empty hole.

A056749.name: Smallest palindrome greater than n in bases 2 and n.

A056752.name: Distance from n! to the nearest prime.

A056753.name: Only odd numbers occur and for all k there are k numbers between any two successive occurrences of k.
formula: Let x = a(n - A164632(n)), a(n) = if (x occured exactly once so far) then x+2 else x. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Aug 23 2009

A056755.name: Number of n-celled polyominoes, where the cells are 1 X 2 rectangles with some of the edges of length 2 replaced by curved arcs that either sag inwards or bulge outwards.

A056756.name: Where n-th prime appears in Euclid-Mullin sequence A000945.

A056757.name: Cube of number of divisors is larger than the number.

A056758.name: Numbers n for which d(n)^3 < n.

A056759.name: The 17 prime powers n = p^w such that d[p^w]^3 > p^w where d = A000005().

A056760.name: Integers with exactly 2 prime divisors such that the cube of the number of divisors exceeds the number.

A056761.name: Odd numbers n such that the cube of the number of divisors of n is greater than n.

A056762.name: Number of terms in A056761 (i.e., odd numbers from A056757) between 2^(n-1) and 2^n.
formula: Occurrences of odd integers x such that 2^(n-1) < x <= 2^n and the cube of number of divisors is larger than the number: A000005(x)^3 > x.

A056763.name: Number of x integers between 2^(n-1) and 2^n for which d(x)^3 > x holds, i.e., cube of number of divisors of x exceeds the number x and binary size of x is n.

A056764.name: Number of integers k below 2^n such that the cube of number of divisors [A000005(k)] is larger than k.

A056765.name: Number of integers from A056757 [defined by A000005(x)^3 > x] not exceeding 2^n.

A056766.name: Smallest term of A056757 (numbers for which the cube of the number of divisors exceeds the number) between 2^(n-1) and 2^n.
formula: Smallest k so that 2^(n-1) < k <= 2^n and A000005(k)^3 > k.

A056767.name: Largest number of binary size n (i.e., between (n-1)-th and n-th powers of 2) with the following property: cube of its number of divisors is larger than the number itself.
formula: Largest terms of A056757 between 2^(n-1) and 2^n.

A056768.name: Number of partitions of the n-th prime into parts that are all primes.
formula: a(n) = A168470(n) + 1. - _Alonso del Arte_, Feb 15 2014, restating the corresponding formula given by _R. J. Mathar_ for A168470.

A056770.name: Smallest number that is n times the product of its digits or 0 if impossible.

A056771.name: a(n) = a(-n) = 34*a(n-1) - a(n-2), and a(0)=1, a(1)=17.
formula: a(n) = T(n, 17) = T(2*n, 3) with T(n, x) Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind. See A053120. T(n, 3)= A001541(n).
a(n) = (a^n + b^n)/2 where a = 17 + 12*sqrt(2) and b = 17 - 12*sqrt(2); sqrt(a(n)-1)/4 = A001109(n). - _James R. Buddenhagen_, Dec 09 2011
a(n) = sqrt(1 + 32*9*A091761(n)^2), n >= 0. See one of the Pell comments above. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Mar 09 2019

A056772.name: Numbers n such that phi(n+4) = phi(n) + 4.

A056773.name: Composite n such that phi(n+4) = phi(n)+4.

A056774.name: Composite n such that phi(n+2) = phi(n)+2.

A056775.name: Numbers k such that phi(k+12) = phi(k) + 12.

A056776.name: Composite numbers k such that phi(k+12) = phi(k) + 12.

A056777.name: Composite n such that both Phi(n+12)=Phi(n)+12 and Sigma(n+12)=Sigma(n)+12.

A056778.name: Number of 3-element antichains on an unlabeled n-element set; equivalence classes of monotone Boolean functions of n variables with 3 mincuts under action of symmetric group S_n.

A056779.name: Number of poly-IH73-tiles (holes allowed) with n cells.

A056780.name: Rectangular free polyominoes: number of n-celled polyominoes when the cell is a rectangle.

A056781.name: Prime powers such that the 4th power of the number of divisors is not smaller than the number itself.
formula: p^w<=(w+1)^4 i.e. p<=(w+1)^(4/w) restricts possible primes and their exponents

A056782.name: Number of 3-element proper antichains (i.e., antichains such that every two members have nonempty intersection) on an unlabeled n-element set.

A056783.name: Number of diamond polyominoes with n cells.

A056784.name: First nonprime in a sequence of consecutive nonprimes which is at least twice as long as any earlier run of consecutive nonprimes in this list.

A056786.name: Number of inequivalent connected planar figures that can be formed from n non-overlapping 1 X 2 rectangles (or dominoes).

A056787.name: Number of incongruental unlabeled undirected trees with n nodes on a square lattice and edges of length 1 or sqrt(2) admitted to the 4 nearest or 4 2nd nearest neighbors.

A056789.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} lcm(k,n)/gcd(k,n).
formula: a(n) = (1/2)*Sum_{d|n} d^2*(d+1) Sum_{j|n/d} mu(j)*j^2. - _Felix A. Pahl_, Nov 23 2019
a(n) = 1 + Sum_{d|n, d > 1} phi(d^3)/2. - _Daniel Suteu_, Dec 10 2020

A056791.name: Weight of binary expansion of n + length of binary expansion of n.
formula: a(n) = a((n - n mod 2) / (2 - n mod 2)) + 1 for n>0, a(0)=1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jul 29 2002
a(n)=sum_{i>=0} 2^b(i) where n=sum_{i>=0} b(i)*2^e(i)is the representation of n. [From _Juri-Stepan Gerasimov_, Jun 06 2010]

A056792.name: Minimal number of steps to get from 0 to n by (a) adding 1 or (b) multiplying by 2.
formula: a(n) = n-valuation(A000254(n), 2) for n>0. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 09 2004
a(n) = (weight of binary expansion of n) + (length of binary expansion of n) - 1.

A056793.name: Number of divisors of lcm(1,...,n).
formula: a(n) = product(floor(log(n)/log(p))+1) where p runs through all prime numbers less than or equal to n. - _Wei Zhou_, Jun 25 2011

A056795.name: Number of divisors of k as k runs through sequence of distinct values of LCM(1,..,n).

A056796.name: Minimal number of steps to get from 0 to n when there are 3 kinds of step: add 1, multiply by 2, multiply by 3.

A056797.name: Numbers n such that 9*10^n+1 is prime.

A056799.name: Numbers n such that 8*9^n +1 is prime.

A056800.name: Numbers n such that 6*9^n +1 is prime.

A056801.name: Numbers k such that 4*9^k + 1 is prime.

A056802.name: Numbers n such that 2*9^n + 1 is prime.

A056803.name: Numbers n such that 12 repeated n times followed by 1 is a palindromic prime.

A056804.name: Numbers n such that 7*10^n + 1 is prime.

A056809.name: Numbers k such that k, k+1 and k+2 are products of two primes.

A056810.name: Numbers n such that the fourth power of n is a palindrome.

A056811.name: Number of primes not exceeding square root of n: primepi(sqrt(n)).
formula: For k = 1, 2, ..., repeat k A069482(k) (that is, prime(k+1)^2 - prime(k)^2) times, and add 0 three times at the beginning (or begin the preceding by k = 0, with prime(0) set to 1). - _Jean-Christophe Hervé_, Oct 30 2013
G.f.: (1/(1 - x)) * Sum_{k>=1} x^(prime(k)^2). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Sep 14 2019

A056812.name: Number of unitary prime factors of lcm[1..n], i.e., primes in LCM with exponent 1.

A056813.name: Largest non-unitary prime factor of LCM(1,...,n); that is, the largest prime which occurs to power > 1 in prime factorization of LCM(1,..,n).
formula: a(n) = prime(w) if prime(w)^2 <= n < prime(w+1)^2.

To get the sequence, repeat 1 three times, and then for any k >= 1, repeat A000040(k) A069482(k) times; or equivalently, for any k >= 1, repeat A008578(k) a number of times equal to A008578(k+1)^2 - A008578(k)^2. - _Jean-Christophe Hervé_, Oct 29 2013

A056814.name: Triangle partitions of order n: topologically distinct ways to dissect a triangle into n triangles.

A056815.name: Primes with prime "look and say" descriptions.

A056816.name: Primes in the tribonacci sequence A000213.

A056818.name: A number n is included if n^2 divides n-th term of A056855.

A056819.name: a(n) = Product_{k|n} (n+1-k).
formula: a(p) = p, for p prime. - _Michel Marcus_, Sep 30 2016

A056820.name: Euler totient function of Cullen numbers (A002064), n*2^n +1.

A056821.name: Totient of the Woodall numbers (A003261), n*2^n -1.

A056823.name: Number of compositions minus number of partitions: A011782(n) - A000041(n).
formula: G.f.: (1 - x) / (1 - 2*x) - Product_{k>=1} 1 / (1 - x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jan 30 2020

A056824.name: Numbers of the form p^(2k+1), p prime, k >= 1.
formula: a(n) ~ n^3 log^3 n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jan 15 2015

A056825.name: Numbers n such that no smaller natural number has the same maximal palindrome in the period of the simple continued fraction for its square root.

A056826.name: Primes p such that (p^p + 1)/(p + 1) is a prime.

A056827.name: a(n) = floor(n^2/6).
formula: a(n) = floor( (1/2) * Sum_{i=1..n+1} (ceiling(i/3) + floor(i/3) - 1) ). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 06 2014

A056828.name: Numbers that are not the sum of at most three powerful (1) numbers.

A056830.name: Alternate digits 1 and 0.
formula: If a(n) is interpreted in base 2:

A056831.name: LCM of composite numbers falling between n-th and (n+1)-st primes.

A056832.name: All a(n) = 1 or 2; a(1) = 1; get next 2^k terms by repeating first 2^k terms and changing last element so sum of first 2^(k+1) terms is odd.
formula: a(1)=1, a(n) = 1 + {sum(i=1, n-1, a(i)*a(n-i)) mod 2}. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 16 2004
a(n) is multiplicative with a(2^e)=1+(1-(-1)^e)/2, a(p^e)=1 if p>2. - _Michael Somos_, Jun 18 2005
a(n)=2 if n-1 is in A079523; a(n)=1 otherwise. - _Vladimir Shevelev_, Jun 22 2009
Asymptotic mean: lim_{m->oo} (1/m) * Sum__{k=1..m} a(k) = 4/3. - _Amiram Eldar_, Mar 09 2021

A056836.name: Distinct values of sequence obtained when LCM is applied to initial segments of sequence A024619 union {1}.

A056841.name: Number of diagonal polyominoes with n cells.

A056842.name: Number of polydrafters: a(n) is the number of polydrafters with n cells.

A056843.name: Number of polydudes(1): a(n) is the number of polydudes with n cells. See the first link for the source of this sequence. The definition is unknown. Not the same as A091130.

A056844.name: Number of polydiamonds: polyominoes made from n diamonds.

A056845.name: Number of polydiamonds: polyominoes made from n diamonds (another version).

A056846.name: Number of polyominoids containing n squares: these are 2-dimensional polyominoes in a three-dimensional grid (edge-connected squares, like the floors, ceilings and walls of a building).

A056847.name: Nearest integer to n - sqrt(n).
formula: G.f.: x/(1-x)^2 - Theta_2(0,x)*x^(3/4)/(2*(1-x)) where Theta_2 is a Jacobi theta function. (End)
a(n) = n - floor(sqrt(n) + 1/2) = n - A000194(n). - _Ridouane Oudra_, May 13 2019

A056848.name: Numbers n such that n divides the number of partitions of n into distinct parts (A000009).

A056851.name: Integers n such that the number of digits in n! is a cube.

A056854.name: a(n) = Lucas(4*n).
formula: a(n) = A000032(4*n), where A000032 = Lucas numbers.

a(n) = 7*S(n-1, 7) - 2*S(n-2, 7) = S(n, 7) - S(n-2, 7) = 2*T(n, 7/2), with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2), S(-1, x) := 0, S(-2, x) := -1. U(n, x), resp. T(n, x), are Chebyshev's polynomials of the second, resp. first, kind. S(n-1, 7) = A004187(n), n>=0. See A049310 and A053120.
a(n) = 2 + 5*Fibonacci(2*n)^2 = 2 + 5*A049684(n), n >= 0. This is in Koshy's book (reference under A065563) 15. on p. 88. Compare with the above Chebyshev T formula. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Aug 27 2012

Let F(x) = Product_{n = 0..inf} (1 + x^(4*n+1))/(1 + x^(4*n+3)). Let alpha = 1/2*(7 - 3*sqrt(5)). This sequence gives the simple continued fraction expansion of 1 + F(alpha) = 2.14242 42709 40138 85949 ... = 2 + 1/(7 + 1/(47 + 1/(322 + ...))).

Also F(-alpha) = 0.85670 72882 04563 14901 ... has the continued fraction representation 1 - 1/(7 - 1/(47 - 1/(322 - ...))) and the simple continued fraction expansion 1/(1 + 1/((7-2) + 1/(1 + 1/((47-2) + 1/(1 + 1/((322-2) + 1/(1 + ...))))))). Cf. A005248.
F(alpha)*F(-alpha) has the simple continued fraction expansion 1/(1 + 1/((7^2-4) + 1/(1 + 1/((47^2-4) + 1/(1 + 1/((322^2-4) + 1/(1 + ...))))))).
a(n) = Fibonacci(4*n+2) - Fibonacci(4*n-2), where Fibonacci(-2) = -1. _Bruno Berselli_, May 25 2015
a(n) = trace(M^n), where M is the 2 X 2 matrix [0, 1; 1, 1]^4 = [2, 3; 3, 5].
Consequently the Gauss congruences hold: a(n*p^k) = a(n*p^(k-1)) (mod p^k) for all prime p and positive integers n and k. See Zarelua and also Stanley (Ch. 5, Ex. 5.2(a) and its solution).
a(2k+1)/7 is the numerator of the continued fraction [3*sqrt(5), 3*sqrt(5), ..., 3*sqrt(5)] with 2k copies of 3*sqrt(5), for k>0. - _Greg Dresden_ and _Tracy Z. Wu_, Sep 10 2020

A056855.name: a(n) = (Product k) * (Sum 1/k), where both the product and the sum are over those positive integers k, where k <= n and gcd(k,n) = 1.
formula: Sum_{1<=m<=n, gcd(m,n)=1} 1/m = (1/n)*Sum_{k|n} mu(n/k)*k*H(k), where H(k) = Sum_{j=1..k} 1/j. - _Leroy Quet_, Nov 13 2004

A056856.name: Triangle of numbers related to rooted trees and unrooted planar trees.
formula: Formula for row n: Sum_{k = 0..n-1} T(n,k)*y^k = Product_{k = 1..n-1} (k + n*y)

E.g.f.: A(x,t) = Sum_{n >= 1} 1/(n*t)*binomial(n*t + n - 1, n)*x^n = log(B_(t+1)(x)), where B_t(x) = Sum_{n >= 0} 1/(n*t + 1)*binomial(n*t + 1, n)*x^n is Lambert's generalized binomial series - see Graham et al., Section 5.4. - _Peter Bala_, Nov 08 2015

A056857.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,c) = number of successive equalities in set partitions of n.
formula: T(n,c) = B(n-1-c)*binomial(n-1, c), where T(n,c) is the number of set partitions of {1, ..., n} that have c successive equalities and B() is a Bell number.

Considered as triangle T(n,k), 0 <= k <= n: T(n,k) = A007318(n,k)*A000110(n-k) and Sum_{k=0..n} T(n,k)*x^k = A000296(n), A000110(n), A000110(n+1), A005493(n), A005494(n), A045379(n) for x = -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 4 respectively. - _Philippe Deléham_, Dec 13 2009
Let R(n,x) denote the n-th row polynomial of the triangle. Then A000110(n+j) = Bell(n+j,1) = Sum_{k = 1..n} R(j,k)*Stirling2(n,k) (Spivey). - _Peter Bala_, Sep 17 2013

A056858.name: Triangle of number of rises in restricted growth strings (RGS) for the set partitions of n.

A056859.name: Triangle of number of falls in set partitions of n.

A056860.name: Triangle T(n,k) = number of element-subset partitions of {1..n} with n-k+1 equalities (n >= 1, 1 <= k <= n).
formula: T(n, k) = binomial(n-1, k-1)*B(k-1) where B denotes the Bell numbers A000110. - _David Callan_, Jul 20 2005

A056861.name: Triangle T(n,k) is the number of restricted growth strings (RGS) of set partitions of {1..n} that have an increase at index k (1<=k<n).

A056862.name: Triangle T(n,k) is the number of restricted growth strings (RGS) of set partitions of {1..n} that have a decrease at index k (1<=k<n).
formula: T(n,k) = B(n) - B(n-1) - A056861(n,k). - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Jun 08 2006

A056863.name: Related to triangle A056858 of number of rises in set partitions of n at a given index i.

A056866.name: Orders of non-solvable groups, i.e., numbers that are not solvable numbers.
formula: A positive integer n is a non-solvable number if and only if it is a multiple of any of the following numbers: a) 2^p(2^2p-1), p any prime. b) 3^p(3^2p-1)/2, p odd prime. c) p(p^2-1)/2, p prime greater than 3 such that p^2+1 = 0 (mod 5). d) 2^4*3^3*13. e) 2^2p(2^2p+1)(2^p-1), p odd prime.

A056867.name: Nilpotent numbers: n such that every group of order n is nilpotent.
formula: n is in this sequence if p^k is not congruent to 1 mod q for any primes p and q dividing n such that p^e but not p^(e+1) divides n and k <= e. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Aug 27 2012

A056868.name: Numbers that are not nilpotent numbers.
formula: n is in this sequence if p^k = 1 mod q for primes p and q dividing n such that p^e but not p^(e+1) divides n and k <= e. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Aug 27 2012

A056869.name: Prime hypotenuses of Pythagorean triangles with consecutive integer sides.

A056870.name: Difference between partial sums of partition numbers (A026905) and partial sums of numbers of partitions into distinct parts (A026906).

A056871.name: Sum of partial sums of partition numbers (A026905) and partial sums of numbers of partitions into distinct parts (A026906).

A056872.name: Numbers n such that n | p(n) + q(n) where p(n) = partition numbers (A000041) and q(n) = partition numbers into distinct parts (A000009).

A056873.name: Numbers n such that n | p(n) - q(n) where p(n) = partition numbers (A000041) and q(n) = partition numbers into distinct parts (A000009).

A056875.name: Generated by sieving the natural numbers: keep the smallest remaining number k and take out its k-th successor l as well as the l-th successor m of l, the m-th successor of m and so on. Then start again from the next remaining number.

A056876.name: Number of permutations (p_1, ..., p_n) of {1,...,n} that are "balanced" in the sense that the sum of k*p_k equals the sum of (n+1-k)*p_k; equivalently, the expected value of k*p_k is (expected value of k) times (expected value of p_k), assuming the uniform distribution.

A056878.name: Number of polyominoes with n cells, symmetric about diagonal 2.

A056879.name: Number of n-celled axially symmetric polyominoes without holes.

A056880.name: Number of n-celled polyominoes without holes, symmetric about axis 2.

A056881.name: Number of n-celled diagonally symmetric polyominoes without holes.

A056882.name: Number of n-celled polyominoes without holes, symmetric about diagonal 2.

A056883.name: Number of n-celled rotationally symmetric polyominoes without holes.

A056884.name: Number of asymmetric n-celled polyominoes without holes.

A056885.name: Triangle T(n,k) = number of minimal covers of an unlabeled n-set that cover k points of that set uniquely, k=0..n.

A056886.name: Determinant of the n X n Hankel matrix whose entries are s_2 (i+j), 0 <= i, j < n, where s_2 is the sum of the base-2 bits.

A056887.name: Determinant of n X n Hankel matrix whose entries are t(i+j), 0 <= i, j < n, where t is the Thue-Morse sequence.

A056888.name: a(n) = number of k such that sum of digits of 9^k is 9n.

A056889.name: Numerators of continued fraction for left factorial.

A056890.name: Denominators of continued fraction for left factorial.

A056891.name: a(n) = (s(n)-(n%2)) / n where s(n) is sequence A006533

A056892.name: a(n) = square excess of the n-th prime.

A056893.name: Smallest prime with square excess of n.
formula: a(n) = min{p in A000040: A053186(p) = n}. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jul 28 2013

A056894.name: If the smallest prime with a square excess of n is p then a(n)=p-n.

A056895.name: If the smallest prime with a square excess of n is p then a(n)^2 = p - n.

A056896.name: Smallest prime which can be written as k^2 + n for k >= 0.
formula: For p a prime: a(p)=p (and a(p-1)=p if p<>3).

A056897.name: Smallest square where a(n)+n is prime.

A056898.name: a(n) = smallest number m such that m^2+n is prime.
formula: For p a prime: a(p) = 0 (and a(p-1) = 1 if p<>3).

A056901.name: Least semiperimeter s of primitive Pythagorean triangle with inradius n.
formula: When n is (i) an odd prime power, s = (n + 1)(n + 2). (ii) a power of 2, s = (n + 1)(2n + 1). (iii) a composite with relatively prime factors a*b such that a is smallest, s = (a + b)(2a + b).

A056902.name: Numbers n where 36n^2+24n+7 is prime (sorted by absolute values with negatives before positives).

A056903.name: Numbers n such that the numerator of the rational number 1 + 1/2 + 1/3 + ... + 1/n is a prime number.

A056904.name: Floor[p/24] where p is a prime which is 4 more than a square.

A056906.name: Numbers k such that 36*k^2 + 5 is prime.

A056907.name: Numbers k such that 36*k^2 + 12*k + 5 is prime (sorted by absolute values with negatives before positives).

A056908.name: Numbers k such that 36*k^2 + 36*k + 13 is prime.

formula: a(n) = (-1 +- sqrt(A056909(n) - 6))/6, choosing +- to give an integer result for each n.

A056913.name: Odd squarefree numbers for which the number of prime divisors is even.

A056915.name: Strong pseudoprimes to bases 2, 3 and 5, i.e., intersection of A001262, A020229, and A020231.

A056916.name: Product of the orders of the elements in a cyclic group with n elements.
formula: a(n) = Product_{ d divides n } d^phi(d). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 10 2004

A056917.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n)-phi(n) is a perfect square.

A056918.name: a(n) = 9*a(n-1)-a(n-2); a(0)=2, a(1)=9.
formula: a(n) = 9*S(n-1, 9) - 2*S(n-2, 9) = S(n, 9) - S(n-2, 9) = 2*T(n, 9/2), with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2) (see A049310), S(-1, x) := 0, S(-2, x) := -1. S(n-1, 9)=A018913(n). U-, resp. T-, are Chebyshev's polynomials of the second, resp. first, kind.
a(n) = ap^n + am^n, with ap := (9+sqrt(77))/2 and am := (9-sqrt(77))/2.

Let F(x) = product {n = 0..inf} (1 + x^(4*n+1))/(1 + x^(4*n+3)). Let alpha = 1/2*(9 - sqrt(77)). This sequence gives the simple continued fraction expansion of 1 + F(alpha) = 2.11095 50589 89701 91909 ... = 2 + 1/(9 + 1/(79 + 1/(702 + ...))).

Also F(-alpha) = 0.88873 23915 40314 47623 ... has the continued fraction representation 1 - 1/(9 - 1/(79 - 1/(702 - ...))) and the simple continued fraction expansion 1/(1 + 1/((9-2) + 1/(1 + 1/((79-2) + 1/(1 + 1/((702-2) + 1/(1 + ...))))))). F(alpha)*F(-alpha) has the simple continued fraction expansion 1/(1 + 1/((9^2-4) + 1/(1 + 1/((79^2-4) + 1/(1 + 1/((702^2-4) + 1/(1 + ...))))))). Cf. A005248.
